WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.550 --> 00:00:01.150
JUDY SINGER: I'm Judy Singer.

00:00:01.150 --> 00:00:02.970
I'm the Senior Vice Provost
for Faculty Development

00:00:02.970 --> 00:00:03.553
and Diversity.

00:00:03.553 --> 00:00:07.850
And I want to welcome you all to
this event on book publishing.

00:00:07.850 --> 00:00:10.980
We have a great panel here,
both from the publishing end

00:00:10.980 --> 00:00:13.120
and from the
faculty end, to help

00:00:13.120 --> 00:00:17.230
provide insights in how
you go from having written

00:00:17.230 --> 00:00:19.640
a dissertation, which I
presume everybody in this room

00:00:19.640 --> 00:00:22.690
has done, and writing a book.

00:00:22.690 --> 00:00:24.980
Some of the people
who are here are

00:00:24.980 --> 00:00:27.449
people who have historically
been book people.

00:00:27.449 --> 00:00:29.490
In other words, when you
wrote your dissertation,

00:00:29.490 --> 00:00:33.330
you actually thought about
framing it in terms of a book.

00:00:33.330 --> 00:00:37.590
Others are making a transition
from having written more

00:00:37.590 --> 00:00:39.520
on the paper side,
and are thinking

00:00:39.520 --> 00:00:44.170
about how you could convert
those ideas into a book length

00:00:44.170 --> 00:00:45.160
manuscript.

00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:46.530
I've written three books.

00:00:46.530 --> 00:00:48.240
I fall in the second camp.

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:51.240
I'm a statistician, so I'm
primarily a paper person.

00:00:51.240 --> 00:00:55.270
But the task of writing
a book is a daunting one.

00:00:55.270 --> 00:00:58.530
There's something about being a
faculty member where everybody

00:00:58.530 --> 00:01:01.880
assumes that somehow, when you
turned in your dissertation

00:01:01.880 --> 00:01:04.950
and you got the sign off from
your advisor and other people

00:01:04.950 --> 00:01:07.370
on your committee, you
magically knew everything

00:01:07.370 --> 00:01:10.290
that you needed to know
about academic publishing.

00:01:10.290 --> 00:01:12.740
And I think one of the things
you're going to hear today

00:01:12.740 --> 00:01:14.820
is, that's not the case.

00:01:14.820 --> 00:01:17.200
And so, for those of you who
are in the midst of writing,

00:01:17.200 --> 00:01:18.970
I think you're probably
confronting that spot on.

00:01:18.970 --> 00:01:20.970
And we hope that this
gives you an opportunity

00:01:20.970 --> 00:01:24.340
to learn from a
distinguished panel about how

00:01:24.340 --> 00:01:26.189
to take those next steps.

00:01:26.189 --> 00:01:27.730
To introduce the
panelists, I'm going

00:01:27.730 --> 00:01:29.438
to introduce my
colleague, Amy Brand, who

00:01:29.438 --> 00:01:31.740
is the Assistant Provost
for Faculty Appointments.

00:01:31.740 --> 00:01:32.420
Thank you.

00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:44.570
AMY BRAND: Good
afternoon and welcome.

00:01:44.570 --> 00:01:48.940
First and foremost, I just
want to say that I'm really

00:01:48.940 --> 00:01:51.060
delighted to have this
panel and, also, to have--

00:01:51.060 --> 00:01:53.029
I think for the first
time in our events

00:01:53.029 --> 00:01:54.695
